column2: Migrated from EPA STORET Legacy Database- originally reported by Wisconsin DNR
First entry of data (collected 072215) - data entered 072315. Clear to partly cloudy- minimal wind. Sighted 1 common loon (Gavia immer) with 1 juvenile.

Sunny - light wind. Loon pair active on the lake. Juvenile loon is now reaching the size of a duck and although it continues to benefit from its mother- it is active in diving and securing food on its own (but is still taking food from mother). As always- lake coloration is moderately stained (making the Seechi disk show a yellowish color).

column1: Water coloration at 10.5 ft. yellowish due to natural mild staining characteristic of North Twin Lake

column2: First data collection for 2016. Clear skies- calm wind (0-5). Common Loon pair have arrived for 2016 breeding season.
Clear- light winds. A pair of Loons are on the lake along with a pair of Trumpeter Swans.

Overcast - some algal development but minor. Water coloration is reddish/yellow which is attributable to this being a "stained" lake. lake level is higher than normal due to the recent heavy rains. The water level is approx. 5" higher than what I would call normal.
Lake clarity is somewhat compromised - this is likely attributable to the recent torrential rains on July 11causing some sedimentation.
Water clarity compromised by more staining than normal- probably due to the amount of rain as it drains into the lake through surrounding bogs.
Stained Water = Red/Yellow Tint; lake Level ~ 1 ft. above "normal"
Stained Water = Red/Yellow Tint; lake Level ~1 ft. above "normal"

Sunny/calm lake. Water tint is actually reddish/yellow ... not just one color. The tint seems deeper in color compared with e-g- last year. Water level still high (est. ~1 ft. above "normal". This is not likely to be a reproductive year for loons. Per observations as a Loon Ranger- water level was an issue in 2016 and water level has been remained higher in 2017. This "seems" to have limited historical nesting sites but- of course- there can be other factors. There was a pair early in the season but one or both sexes disappeared for unknown reasons.
Calm conditions - lake level still higher than normal but has been headed toward more normal levels over the last 6-8 weeks.

Calm Lake - lake level still above normal due to recent autumn rain events. Since North Twin Lake is a stained drainage lake- I am assuming that the rain events of 2016/2017 has resulted in more drainage from wetlands/bogs and- therefore- the water clarity is somewhat compromised by increased tannins in the water.
Calm wind - clear sky with some high level clouds
The usual degree of stain (tannins) in the water.
Stained water as usual - Lake level is the highest I have seen since moving here in 2014.
Stained water as always - coloration is more of a combination of red/yellow

Weather clear with light NW winds. Normal date but the trend in recent times has been toward less clarity which is likely related to heavy rains in the last 2-3 years causing more runoff and drainage from surrounding wetlands/bogs.
Despite no excessive rains since last data collection- the Secchi reading has worsened
Clear day- light winds. A pair of territorial loons were sighted and have been under observation since April 18. Clear weather- light winds temp low 60's.
